SINGULAR VS PLURALS
76
Rules for Forming Plural Nouns in English
Plural nouns are used when referring to more than one person, place, thing, or idea. Here are the most
common rules for forming plurals:
 Add "-s" to Most Nouns
• For most singular nouns, simply add "-s" to make them plural.
o Example:
▪ Car → Cars
▪ Book → Books
▪ Dog → Dogs
 Add "-es" to Nouns Ending in "-s", "-ss", "-sh", "-ch", "-x", or "-z"
• If a noun ends in -s, -ss, -sh, -ch, -x, or -z, add "-es" to make it plural.
o Example:
▪ Bus → Buses
▪ Brush → Brushes
▪ Box → Boxes
▪ Church → Churches
▪ Buzz → Buzzes
 Change "-y" to "-ies" if Preceded by a Consonant
• If a noun ends in "-y" and there is a consonant before it, change "y" to "ies".
o Example:
▪ City → Cities
▪ Baby → Babies
▪ Lady → Ladies
• Exception: If there is a vowel before "-y", just add "-s".
o Example:
▪ Toy → Toys
▪ Day → Days
▪ Key → Keys
 Change "-f" or "-fe" to "-ves"
• Some nouns ending in "-f" or "-fe" change to "-ves" in the plural.
o Example:
▪ Leaf → Leaves
▪ Wolf → Wolves
▪ Knife → Knives
▪ Life → Lives
77
• Exceptions: Some nouns just add "-s" instead.
o Example:
▪ Roof → Roofs
▪ Chef → Chefs
▪ Cliff → Cliffs
 Irregular Plurals (Completely Change Form)
• Some nouns change completely in the plural form.
o Example:
▪ Man → Men
▪ Woman → Women
▪ Child → Children
▪ Tooth → Teeth
▪ Foot → Feet
▪ Mouse → Mice
▪ Goose → Geese
 Some Nouns Stay the Same in Singular & Plural
• These nouns have the same singular and plural form.
o Example:
▪ Sheep → Sheep
▪ Deer → Deer
▪ Fish → Fish
▪ Moose → Moose
▪ Aircraft → Aircraft
 Latin & Greek Nouns with Special Plural Forms
• Some nouns from Latin or Greek have special plural endings.

📝 Answer Key (For Teachers or Self-Check)
Here are the correct plural forms:
Part 1: Regular Plurals
• Car → Cars
• Book → Books
• Table → Tables
• Brush → Brushes
• Box → Boxes
• Bus → Buses
• Dress → Dresses
• Watch → Watches
• Tomato → Tomatoes
• Potato → Potatoes
83
Part 2: Nouns Ending in "-y"
• Baby → Babies
• City → Cities
• Story → Stories
• Lady → Ladies
• Country → Countries
• Party → Parties
• Fly → Flies
• Library → Libraries
• Family → Families
• Army → Armies
Part 3: Nouns Ending in "-f" or "-fe"
• Leaf → Leaves
• Wolf → Wolves
• Knife → Knives
• Wife → Wives
• Life → Lives
• Thief → Thieves
• Calf → Calves
• Loaf → Loaves
• Shelf → Shelves
• Self → Selves
Part 4: Irregular Plurals
• Child → Children
• Man → Men
• Woman → Women
• Tooth → Teeth
• Foot → Feet
• Mouse → Mice
• Goose → Geese
• Person → People
• Louse → Lice
• Ox → Oxen
Part 5: Same Singular & Plural
• Sheep → Sheep
• Deer → Deer
• Fish → Fish
• Moose → Moose
• Salmon → Salmon
• Species → Species
• Aircraft → Aircraft
• Series → Series
• Swine → Swine
• Offspring → Offspring
Part 6: Latin & Greek Plurals
• Cactus → Cacti
84
• Radius → Radii
• Bacterium → Bacteria
• Phenomenon → Phenomena
• Criterion → Criteria
• Thesis → Theses
• Index → Indices (or Indexes)
• Nucleus → Nuclei
• Syllabus → Syllabi
• Medium → Media
Part 7: Compound Nouns
• Mother-in-law → Mothers-in-law
• Passer-by → Passers-by
• Attorney General → Attorneys General
• Commander-in-chief → Commanders-in-chief
• Editor-in-chief → Editors-in-chief
• Brother-in-law → Brothers-in-law
• Father-in-law → Fathers-in-law
